05923nam a22008415i 9780226390901DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226390901  a(DE-B1597)524235  a(OCoLC)963934712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHD9665.5b.T46 2017 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a303.48322300aTherapeutic Revolutions :bPharmaceuticals and Social Change in the Twentieth Century /ced. by Jeremy A. Greene, Flurin Condrau, Elizabeth Siegel Watkins. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b4 halftones, 8 line drawings, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Medicine Made Modern by Medicines -- t1. Futures and their Uses -- t2. Reconceiving the Pill -- t3. Magic Bullet in the Head? -- t4. Revolutionary Markets? -- t5. Recurring Revolutions? -- t6. Pharmaceutical Geographies -- t7. After McKeown -- t8. Chemotherapy in the Shadow of Antiretrovirals -- t9. Volatility, Speculation, and Therapeutic Revolutions in Nigerian Drug Markets -- t10. Therapeutic Evolution or Revolution? -- t11. A Therapeutic Revolution Revisited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen asked to compare the practice of medicine today to that of a hundred years ago, most people will respond with a story of therapeutic revolution: Back then we had few effective remedies, but now we have more (and more powerful) tools to fight disease, from antibiotics to psychotropics to steroids to anticancer agents. This collection challenges the historical accuracy of this revolutionary narrative and offers instead a more nuanced account of the process of therapeutic innovation and the relationships between the development of medicines and social change. These assembled histories and ethnographies span three continents and use the lived experiences of physicians and patients, consumers and providers, and marketers and regulators to reveal the tensions between universal claims of therapeutic knowledge and the actual ways these claims have been used and understood in specific sites, from postwar West Germany pharmacies to twenty-first century Nigerian street markets. By asking us to rethink a story we thought we knew, Therapeutic Revolutions offers invaluable insights to historians, anthropologists, and social scientists of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPharmaceutical industryxSocial aspects. 0aTherapeuticsxSocial aspects. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  abiomedicine.  aconsumer history.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory of science.  amedical anthropology.  amodern medicine.  apharmaceutical industry.  aprescription drugs.  atherapeutic revolution.  atwentieth century history.1 aBasilico, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonah, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondrau, Flurin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCondrau, Flurin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarmer, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Jeremy A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Jeremy A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHenckes, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKehr, Janina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessel, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c